DATES OF COMPOSITION AND {hammon—In Cicero’s letters to Atticus written during the summer of 45 B.c., when he was in retirement from public life (see p. xi), there are many references to his work on this treatise. Writing from Astura on May 13, and alluding to the death of his daughter, he says : ‘ Ego hic duo magna συντάγματα absolvi 3 nullo enim alio modo a miseria quasi aberrare possum ' (Att. xii. 45. 1). On May 29, he writes from Tusculum (Att. xiii. 32. 3): ‘ Torquatus Romaest ; misi ut tibi daretur. Catulum et Lucullum ut opinor antea; his libris nova prohoemia sunt addita quibus eorum uterque laudatur.' Here ‘ Torquatus ' means the first two books of De Finibus, and ‘Catulus ’ the first and ‘ Lucullus ' the second book of Academica in its first shape ; so it is the latter treatise‚ and not De F inibus I. and 11.‚ that is probably referred to by the modest expression in the preceding quotation ‘ two big compilations.’ We infer that Academica in its first form was so far finished by the latter half of May that a copy was sent to Atticus, new prefaces being added a little later.
